<TITLE> Central Asia to spend $19 bln on transport links </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 DUSHANBE, Nov 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Central Asian nations plan to build roads and railways costing $19 billion over the next decade to revive the region's role as a major trading link between Asia and Europe. The countries agreed with China, Mongolia and other regional players at a weekend conference organised by the Asia Development Bank to modernise existing routes and build six new ones to link up with Russia, India, and south-east Asia. "Even though Central Asia lies at the centre of the Eurasian continent, less than 1 percent of all trade between Europe and Asia currently goes through the region," said Liqun Jin, ADB's vice-president. "Inadequate transport infrastructure and cumbersome border processes have resulted in nearly all trade going by sea." ADB's Central Asia Regional Economic Cooperation (CAREC) initiative includes Afghanistan, Azerbaijan, China, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Mongolia, Tajikistan and Uzbekistan. Participants agreed to borrow $18.7 billion from international financial institutions and tap their own state budgets to finance the project. Central Asian nations are growing rapidly on the back of high world prices for their key exports, metals and energy. But ageing Soviet infrastructure and lack of modern roads and border crossings have hampered the region's global integration. The former Soviet region, especially its economic powerhouse Kazakhstan, is expected to be a major source of new crude oil supplies over the next decade as the West weeks to diversify its energy needs away from Russia and the Middle East. Kazakhstan's location means it must export its products through other countries to reach Western markets. It has vowed to build more pipelines and roads, and open up its airspace to more cargo and passenger flights to boost Europe-Asia shipments via the regi
